<tr bgcolor="#7EB4FA">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>robertsvard</b>
<br>3 November 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn? revisited!</b>
<br>
<p>Wow! Alot of great responses! I realize that it is kind of awkward to critizie a game on it's own revival site. Well, no real flames so far. Thank you all. As to my own personal taste, it was just a run up to the main gist of the message, which was directed to RedBrick themselves. So let's leave my taste out of it. <p></p>The main gist, and I quote myself: "who will buy these sourcebooks, the total being worth something like a smaller car? Is there truly a market for it? Is it all really that good? Is all the material really useful? Publish new books with a concentrated material instead of just rehashing the old stuff."<p></p>The old material is all out there. Except the really good stuff which might have sold out (but this should be reprinted). 95% of the textmass in the products are just that, text. Even if RedBrick plans a major overhaul of the rulessystem, there will still only be very little material that really needs reprinting.<p></p>I am talking economics here. Does anyone here have any idea of how mindboggling expensive it is to put out all these books? As the title of the original post asks: why did ED fail in the first place? For those who didn't get it: Too much crap, too few gems. Too many books on the market (=huge investment), diluted sales (=low returns). It just doesn't make sense. There is also the time perspective! How long does a game "survive on the market"? How long does RedBrick have to market and sell all those books and supplements before the market looses interest in Earthdawn Classic?  Could it be 2 years? 4 years? 6 years? Even the really long running systems (like Shadowrun, Star Wars, MERP) didn't last that long. AD&amp;D 3.5 ED is quite a long way gone from D&amp;D. A short time span requires a larger density of books which risks either outrunning the fans (the last third of the books arrives as the first third of the buyers looses interest in the game/hobby) or swamping them (2 books a month? How much money does people actually have to spend on RPG books?).<p></p>Also, finally, it has been proven without a doubt that Earthdawn already failed on the open market (on both the English and Japanese language markets for that matter!). The challange that faces RedBrick is to find out why it failed and fix the problem. I have, in the original post given my reason as to why ED failed in the first attempt, I'll restate them:<p></p>1. FASA put out books full of useless stuff, resulting in a low value per book ratio, thus scaring of buyers. <p></p>Personal example: I bought the first two adventures, and then never bought an adventure again, as they were fairly useless to me. Out of the excellent Thera supplement, a gem, I could only use about one quarter of the text. I never even bothere buying the supplements that came after, although I like Cara Fadh (it was to peripheral and the material I already had was good enough for my own campaigns).<p></p>If this wasn't true, then why didn't more people buy all the books? The ideal ratio should be 1 copy of every supplement for every rule book sold. What was the original ED up to? 1:5? 1:10? Does anyone have any un-classified figures?<p></p>2. FASA put out too many books, resulting in making products that competed with other products in the same genre! This is fine if we are talking McDonalds (it is, or was, their strategy) but in an investement intesive business as the one FASA was in, it is economic suicide. For people who doubt me, take a look at how the mobile phone industry works. The cell phones that I have here in Japan are 2 years ahead of the "state of the art" phones released in the States/Europe.<p></p>Personal example: Let me see, of the 2 magic supplements, do I really need to buy any of them? Or is it safe to stick with the magic rules (that work beautifully, and that I haven't even explored fully yet) already in the rulebook?<p></p>If this wasn't true, what are all those unsold ED books doing in the warehouse? (this sounds funny when I read it over again, but think of it: a company does not want to produce too many copies of anything, if they did their planning, they would know the sell rate (or at least be able to make an estimate that is 90% accurate) and thus not produce too many books!)<p></p>The sum of it all, if anyone is still reading this is:<p></p>1. RedBrick needs to find out why the original ED failed and address those failures (be they poor planning, poor marketing, poor products or whatever) with a realistic plan.<p></p>And hence,<p></p>It is my oppinion that RedBrick falls right into the trap of the old ED. Too many books, too low quality over all.<p></p>So, my suggestion to RedBrick is: Republish only the REALLY good stuff, and do it fairly quickly. This to capture a new generation of players. Use massive marketing to punch a hole in the wet blanket that is D20. Write NEW stuff that is at least as good as the stuff you have just republished. This is to get the old fans back. <p></p>Quite frankly, at my present company (doing product development) I would be fired for even suggesting a market plan such as the one just made public for Earthdawn Classic. 25 old fans on a forum is not going to be of any help, at all.<p></p>And finally 1, yes, I love Earthdawn, why else would I be here? And finally 2, may I recommend cheap ass Chinese printing? Cool paper and binding, vivid colours, cheap distribution and low low prices!<p></p>In replying to this, please limit your comments to the meaty parts of this post. There's no need to "attack my love of ED", or accuse me of being grumpy. I would love RedBrick to come with a reply starting... <p></p>"Yes! We have already discussed ALL of the things that you mention, and here is what we are going to do about it (we just didn't want to make our strategy public until now):"<p></p>Yours, R, Tokyo.</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#A0D5FF">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>Excelvior</b>
<br>3 November 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn? revisited!</b>
<br>
<p>I have to agree with the friend from Japan.<br>I also ADORE Earthdawn, but I am not enough for it to succeed (neither the 25 old fans in the forum as robertsvard said).<br>The market here in Greece (well, I am from Greece and it is the only market I know and I can speak of) has become very difficult. Book prices are extremely high, for example the new Dragonlance book costs 50 Euro. The average salary in Greece is about 800 Euros/month... You can easily understand what sacrifices a RPG-maniac has to take in order to get what he wants. Another fact to take care of is that I believe Earthdawn is a game not known to many. I would say that FASA didn't spend much money or time in advertisment. Ask 30 gamers (in Greece of course) about ED, only one will have heard of it.<br>My advice to you : Reprint some of the old books in tomes (3 books to 1 hardcover) and make a selection of the "gems" robertsvard said about. Take opinions from as many old ED fans as you can. Advertise your stuff in RPG sites, shops, markets. Learn first what the market needs and how you can provide it.<br>We will be here in every step, helping as best as we can. This game you trying to sell is something we love and we want to buy, as long as it worths it.<p></p>Byron<p></p>P.S Sorry for any mistakes, my English are not that good... well I guess neither are your Greek :)</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#7EB4FA">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>James Flowers</b>
<br>3 November 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn? revisited!</b>
<br>
<p>"R" (Robert?)<p></p>I'll attempt to respond to your posting as follows, although I come away from reading your posts with the very clear picture that we aren't going to producing anything that you are going to be interested in purchasing...<p></p>Caveat: Please do take the time to read my entire response before you pre-judge my reaction to your posting.<p></p>Firstly, in *my* response to your original posting (I can't speak for other people), I did ask for some *constructive* feedback. I don't believe that you have actually provided anything "constructive" at all to date, particularly with this post, which simply seems to be a rehash of your original post.<p></p>You have made it very clear that you: a) seem happy with the game rules as they stand; b) don't really seem enamoured of the supplements and sourcebooks to date (since you don't like most of the "fluff" and possibly want more "crunch"?); c) don't seems to like the adventures that much. *shrug* I reiterate, this is all entirely YOUR opinion. And you are very welcome to express it. I think you've expressed it enough now, though.<p></p>My response to your other comments (interested readers, please reference these back to the original posting). My apologies in advance if I don't cover all of these in detail:<p></p>"Who will buy these sourcebooks?" I think a lot of Earthdawn gamers will. I think that you won't, since they will "probably" contain a similar content makeup. Whether they do follow the FASA format is in part based on feedback from Earthdawn gamers. I am taking your vote as a "No".<p></p>"Is there truly a market for it?" From the response we've had to date? Absolutely.<p></p>"Is all the material really useful?" The usefulness of the material will vary from gamer to gamer. If it ends up following the FASA format because that is what the gamers who provide us with specific feedback say they want, then I suspect you won't be purchasing much of our material. Otherwise, if the format changes and aligns itself "by concensus" to something that is closer to what you yourself may want, then you might.<p></p>"Publish new books with a concentrated material instead of just rehashing the old stuff." We're not planning to simply "rehash the old stuff" any more than we need to. And from our perspective, that means getting as much information into the rulebooks (i.e. rules), into the sourcebooks (i.e. source information), etc., as possible. The new supplements and sourcebooks are intended to be primarily *new* -- if there's any existing information on some of the topics covered by these, then it will be re-used. How much of a mix that results in (old to new) will vary, but I doubt there will be worse than a 50/50 mix in even the extreme cases.<p></p>"Does anyone here have any idea of how mindboggling expensive it is to put out all these books?" Yes, we do. Otherwise we wouldn't have pursued this property in the first place. I'm not sure you do? Nothing you have said to this point gives me the impression you are qualified to talk about producing roleplaying games?<p></p>"Why did ED fail in the first place?" It failed for many reasons. You do raise some interesting questions in this paragraph. Thanks for that. I'm not sure that your're talking about just Earthdawn or whether your comments couldn't apply to almost any roleplaying game line? The fact of the matter is that Earthdawn *has* survived for a very long time. We've taken into account the relative size of our market in our business plan. And we've still decided to continue. That's all I have to say on this matter.<p></p>"The challange that faces RedBrick is to find out why it failed and fix the problem." Ah, *now* you're getting my interest. But all you've really done is expressed an opinion on why YOU think the game line failed. Admittedly, I would like to think that this is an opinion shared by your fellow gamers, so I can't exclude it completely out-of-hand as being invalid. But it is still only an opinion. The only way you would find out why the game line was "unsuccessful" would be to get an answer from FASA. And I can't answer for them.<p></p>Now, here's some homework for you. Send me an email with a detailed breakdown of exactly why you think the game line failed, point by point. Include any numbers or statistics you have to back up your allegations. Cold hard facts please. Because everything I've read to date -- statistics and numbers shw that the game line was actually very successful? Whether we can turn the current trend around and resurrect that potential will simply be a test of our business plan and time.<p></p>Moving on...<p></p>"1. FASA put out books full of useless stuff, resulting in a low value per book ratio, thus scaring of buyers... If this wasn't true, then why didn't more people buy all the books? " Ah. Now you lost my interest again. I think this is your opinion showing again. Joy! My interest is back! I'm curious as to how you qualify your ratios though? Can you back these up with fact? Can you compare this ratio with, say, a popular game line like WW's Exalted? AEG's 7th Sea? DP9's Tribe 8? Even WotC's Dungeons and Dragons?<p></p>"2. FASA put out too many books, resulting in making products that competed with other products in the same genre!" Maybe. Again, in your opinion. My opinion? I don't think they put enough books out. I qualify that by saying that, for instance: "My campaign draws extensively on the background materials produced by FASA. There are a number of areas that my players have begun exploring that I don't have a clear vision of, for example, Rugaria. While I am currently creating my own campaign material for use in this area, I find that my time is limited and I would have liked it if FASA had done more with this province." Hmmm... That's still a bit opinionistic. My real reasons are (another example): "I have less time these days to develop Earthdawn campaign material, therefore I would appreciate it if FASA or whoever creates and publishes more Earthdawn material on these areas: Rugaria, Vasgothia, wherever. I would really like it if any new sourcebooks contained a more detailed history and timeline, particularly of events following the end of the Scourge and leading up to ABC. Also, can you please include more detailed maps of the area? There weren't enough maps in the original supplements and that would save me a lot of time. More creatures would be useful as well. Etc..." Of course, if you aren't interested in using the Fourth World, then very little of this material is going to be useful anyway. *shrugs*<p></p>More homework. Drop me an email and give me your ideas on what you would like to see from the supplements given in RedBrick's Publication Roster. Be as specific as you can. Step outside the bubble and pretend that you design games for a living and you are looking at producing supplements for a passionate fan community. Consider that you want to try and grow the market. Now, take a deep breath and let us know what *you* would like to see.<p></p>Moving on...<p></p>"What are all those unsold ED books doing in the warehouse?" I don't know. Perhaps FASA over-estimated the market when they did their print volume calculations? Perhaps there was a really good price break at 10000 copies that made it cheaper compared to 5000? It's a big mystery really... *grin* I think the question you want to ask here is "Is RedBrick going to do this as well? Because that would be crazy!" And the answer is: "No. RedBrick is not going to go and print thousands of copies of supplements in order to help feed the silverfish population and assist with the deforestation of the planet." Or just: "No." We are not over-estimating our market and our sell rate. Conversely, we are not "under-estimating" our market either. That would be a more heinous crime, IMO.<p></p>"1. RedBrick needs to find out why the original ED failed and address those failures (be they poor planning, poor marketing, poor products or whatever) with a realistic plan." We have a realistic plan.<p></p>"It is my oppinion that RedBrick falls right into the trap of the old ED. Too many books, too low quality over all." I don't think you can say this based on your comments to date. Particularly the quality comment. That's way off the target. I'll comment on why I think this is the case further down.<p></p>"Republish only the REALLY good stuff, and do it fairly quickly." What we think is the material worth republishing is already in the pipeline. Whether it's the REALLY good stuff will be determined by the market.<p></p>"Use massive marketing to punch a hole in the wet blanket that is D20." We have a marketing budget. I wouldn't call it a massive marketing budget. Are you offering to bankroll our marketing campaign, though? *smile* And I wouldn't even deem to call d20 a wet blanket.<p></p>"Write NEW stuff that is at least as good as the stuff you have just republished. This is to get the old fans back." Hmm. This seems contradictory to me. Well, the republished stuff will be mainly FASA stuff. And I got the impression that you weren't that keen on most of the FASA stuff. Oh, I get it! *penny drops* You mean write NEW material that is at least as good as the REALLY good stuff? OK. We're going to try VERY hard to do exactly that. *smile*<p></p>Whether it meets your standards? Well, see the previous homework exercise and add another entry: please provide us with some examples of what you deem to be REALLY good stuff so that we can avoid the REALLY bad stuff.<p></p>"I would be fired for even suggesting a market plan such as the one just made public for Earthdawn Classic." What marketing plan? We haven't posted up our marketing plan? Did I miss something? We have posted an INDICATION of what RedBrick is thinking of producing by way of products. This is based on feedback from the Earthdawn community and, while it looks like a lot of books, it might not end up being anyehere the number presented. Interestingly enough, our first releases aren't even shown on the roster. What this is intended to do is to engender some feedback and debate. And offline, through email, it has done this. But people will be invited to provide suggestions on what they do or don't want to see "on the roster" and the "order of preference" they would like. But it's NOT a marketing plan. Perhaps I should modify the document to make that clearer? Hmmmmm... As for our REAL "marketing plan" -- we may share that in time. We are hoping to share some of our business experiences with the world in order to provide gamers with an idea of what REALLY goes on behind the scenes.<p></p>In answer to the previous "too low quality overall?", I am surprised that you could even make this comment? Particularly considering we haven't released anything yet... If you are basing your comment on the INDICATIVE Publications Roster, then you've done a lot of reading between the lines. Can you please be more specific? I've had nothing but positive response from the "draft" material we have put together to date.<p></p>"25 old fans on a forum is not going to be of any help, at all." I'm not sure where this comment comes from? There's a lot more Earthdawn gamers out there? Unless you are referring to the number of gamers who have provided you with feedback to date? I'm confused...<p></p>Moving on...<p></p>"I love Earthdawn, why else would I be here?" Something we ABSOLUTELY both agree on Robert! *grin* Why else would I risk a lot of money, the love of my family, and all of my unallocated time for the forseeable future doing this? And the same can be said for those who been working with us on this project for the last year (well, almost a year) to get us to this point.<p></p>"May I recommend cheap ass Chinese printing?" And a good suggestion Robert. We've already considered using out-of-country printers. If you can provide us (email please) with some contacts, we would be happy to ask for quotes. Quality is VERY important to us, however.<p></p>"In replying to this, please limit your comments to the meaty parts of this post. There's no need to "attack my love of ED", or accuse me of being grumpy." I didn't attack you in your previous post. I can't say the same of others... I may, however, come across as somewhat scathing or critical with my responses here to your latest missive. Those who know me, even those I've met in the last few weeks, will know that I am passionate about Earthdawn. And RedBrick, the collective staff and support team, are passionate about making this a success.<p></p>"Yes! We have already discussed ALL of the things that you mention, and here is what we are going to do about it (we just didn't want to make our strategy public until now)." OK then: Yes! We have already discussed (almost) ALL of the things that you mention, plus many more as well that you haven't. As for making our strategy public? Not yet. Way too early for that. Please be patient... All things in time.<p></p>Finally from me, I've seen a lot of comments from roleplayers over the years saying "Oh, I could do a better job" or "I could just setup a publishing company and make really good roleplaying games" and so on. But the difference between "saying it" and "doing it" is vast. Well, RedBrick is doing it. And we're carrying the risk for you. And we're actually interested in what you, our "current" customers have to say, because we think you have a lot to contribute. But it is going to take time to put those mechanisms in place and, in the meantime, we're not sitting around twiddling our thumbs waiting -- we're wanting to get some products out the door as quickly as we can so that you (the customer) can decide whether we are doing the right thing by you (the customer). There's nothing novel or new about this idea. We like it and want to try it out. We are probably going to make some decisions that some people are not going to be happy with (you can't please everyone). Only time will tell if it works or not. But we intend to be as flexible as we can when it comes to creating material for the Earthdawn game line.<p></p>Robert, if you are interested in responding IN DETAIL, WITH SPECIFICS to this posting, please do me the courtesy of emailing it to me to the address on the Contact Us page. I welcome a detailed dialogue with you, but I suspect we're going to continue a serious debate/counter-debate in this forum and it's not really the place for it. If there are any points in our future discussions that you feel should be made public, then I am happy to post those up for comments and review.<p></p>What I don't to happen is for this forum to be used for personal attacks of any kind -- against posters, against the game, and against us (although I have broad shoulders). This will also keep the amount of time I have to spend replying at length to these sorts of posts (and this is not the only place I've had to do that) to a minimum. The return on that is I can actually do some work on producing quality products for the Earthdawn game line. *grin* That I think you will agree is the ultimate goal...<p></p>Again, thank you for taking the time to post your well-intentioned comments.<p></p>Kind regards,<p></p>JAMES FLOWERS<br>Line Developer, RedBrick Limited</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
