<tr bgcolor="#A0D5FF">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>LouP</b>
<br>4 November 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn? revisited!</b>
<br>
<p>I'm going to respond to a couple of points in this discussion that seem to me to be off-base. Of course, since this post is essentially saying that I did a terrible job in guiding the ED line at FASA, I should probably stay out of this, but I'll try to keep my comments (mostly) civil.<p></p>==== Begin Quote ====<br>Also, finally, it has been proven without a doubt that Earthdawn already failed on the open market (on both the English and Japanese language markets for that matter!).<br>==== End Quote ====<p></p>I disagree that this has been proven without a doubt, especially since we see LRG continuing to publish ED material. <p></p>
<br>==== Begin Quote ====<br> The challange that faces RedBrick is to find out why it failed and fix the problem. I have, in the original post given my reason as to why ED failed in the first attempt, I'll restate them:<p></p>1. FASA put out books full of useless stuff, resulting in a low value per book ratio, thus scaring of buyers. <p></p>Personal example: I bought the first two adventures, and then never bought an adventure again, as they were fairly useless to me. Out of the excellent Thera supplement, a gem, I could only use about one quarter of the text. I never even bothere buying the supplements that came after, although I like Cara Fadh (it was to peripheral and the material I already had was good enough for my own campaigns).<br>==== End Quote ====<p></p>ED was published based on a model with an emphasis on providing lots of background information rather than lots of rules. Simply because you didn't find the majority of the ED supplements useful doesn't mean that the rest of the ED audience didn't.<p></p>Personally, I consider some of the ED supplements FASA produced (including the Serpent River, Throal: The Dwarf Kingdom, and Dragons) among the BEST RPG supplements published at that time.<p></p>==== Begin Quote ====<br>If this wasn't true, then why didn't more people buy all the books? The ideal ratio should be 1 copy of every supplement for every rule book sold. What was the original ED up to? 1:5? 1:10? Does anyone have any un-classified figures?<br>==== End Quote ====<p></p>This comment speaks volumes about what you don't know about the game industry. While it may be true that an ideal ratio would be to sell 1 copy of each supplement for each copy of the rulebook sold, this NEVER happens for ANY game. Not even D&amp;D. Many game groups make due with only 1 or 2 copies of the rules, and some never even bother with supplements at all. To say that the game failed because it's supplement sales didn't match the rulebook sales is just plain wrong.<p></p>As for ratios, I know that FASA sold roughly 40,000 - 45,000 copies of the ED rulebook, and the highest selling supplements probably sold only half that.<p></p>==== Begin Quote ====<br>2. FASA put out too many books, resulting in making products that competed with other products in the same genre! This is fine if we are talking McDonalds (it is, or was, their strategy) but in an investement intesive business as the one FASA was in, it is economic suicide. <br>==== End Quote ====<p></p>FASA never put out more than 8 ED products in a single year. In fact, during the last two years that FASA published ED, we published only 4 books per year. That's hardly too many.<p></p>Of course FASA produced books that competed with other products in the same genre. How would you suggest a company produce products for a FANTASY RPG that DOESN'T complete with other fantasy RPGs? Again, your comments tell me that you know next to nothing about the game industry. All they say is that you have an narrow vision of what you like in RPGs and that ED doesn't fit your tastes.<p></p>Take Care,<p></p>Lou Prosperi<br>Former ED Line Developer</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
