<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>robertsvard</b>
<br>4 November 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn? revisited!</b>
<br>
<p>Dear Lou, what have I done to deserve a reply from you? I love Earthdawn. It is my favourite Fantasy game. I have almost all the products. You are right, I do know next to nothing about publishing role playing games. You are right, most of my comments are really really personal reflections. <p></p>What I wanted to do with this post is not to attack RedBrick, I will be the first to stand in line to pick up their new products. Neither did I want to attack FASA (as my favourite game overall is Shadowrun, and my second favourite game is Earthdawn, FASA has provided me with well over 50% of my greatest gaming experiences). <p></p>I voiced my fears about RedBrick perhaps not being able to carry out their plans succesfully, for reasons I've mentioned earlier. I do, really, really, hope that Earthdawn will live long and prosper and make all of the great people at RedBrick richer than Croesus.<p></p>However, in my narrow ways of expressing myself (i.e. looking like an attack rather than "I'm scared! Tell me you will carry this one through!") I have obviously managed to anger a few people. So I will offer my sincere apologies and step back, retracting all my comments and do just what was asked of me: "Wait and see". <p></p>Sorry RedBrick, and good luck.<br>Sorry Mr. Prosperi, and thanks for all the hard work you have given us during the years, succesfully bringing out a game that has given many people a lot of joy. <p></p>The one thing that I know with 100% surety about the Role Playing Games Industry is that it is not a walk in the park.<p></p>As for all the innocent bystanders caught in this cross-fire, sorry.<p></p>Yours, Robert, Tokyo.</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
