<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#A0D5FF">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>LadsoBarsaive</b>
<br>5 November 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn? revisited!</b>
<br>
<p>Hello:<p></p>I think this thread alone can be a good example of what is needed to keep Earthdawn going...constructive criticism, and good alternatives.<p></p>Everyone has their beefs about any random gaming system. Being able to back them up with hard numbers, concrete examples, or even reasonable suggestions/options is better than a supersized screed that basically says "Um, it sucked before, and you'll make it suck now..."<p></p>This is why I'm not interested in the chat about this that's happening on other RPG sites, becuase those people are complaining there, and not getting themselves HERE, and offering to help.<p></p>If you're not part of the solution, you're part of the problem! No, everyone won't always be happy with what gets put out for an RPG...but there are duaris of what people want, and damn clear examples of what worked, and what sold.<p></p>I hope people voice concerns/issues/thoughts that can help Redbrick, and I hope they contribute to making it better and not just sitting around complaining before/during/after the fact.<p></p>It's rare in the commercial world to be able to get in on the ground floor (maybe we should call this the mezzanine) of something, and help to make it "good". <p></p>Now's your chance, everyone.</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#7EB4FA">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>Kerym</b>
<br>10 November 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn? revisited!</b>
<br>
<p>Well it has been ten years now that Earthdawn has been a part of my life.  I still have my first printing, beat to hell and back, taped and crippled hardcover of the rulebook (it has been through alot of abuse).  <p></p>Eitherway I love the game, loved the products produced for it initially by FASA then LRG, and am sure I will be buying stuff from you guys.  I won't even speculate why FASA dropped Earthdawn, I was not there so anything I could say would be conjecture not fact.  My opinion however on what you are doing is simple.  RedBrick is involving it's existing customer base heavily in the process of marketing this game we all love.  <p></p>One thing has struck me over the 25 years I have been gaming or gm-ing, a game is rarely successful because of the amount of advertising dollars.  What pushes most games from obscurity to success is word of mouth.  I have had amazing success with getting people to play ED over the years because these gamers value my opinion more than a full color add, or popup on a website.  If RedBrick continues to involve its customer base it will find it difficult to fail.</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#A0D5FF">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>beansidhe</b>
<br>10 November 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn? revisited!</b>
<br>
<p>Kerym, I couldn't agree more. It's people who play the game and love the game getting out there and talking to people that will cause the fanbase to grow. Advertising IS necessary to some extent to get the name in front of people, but very few gamers are going to go spend money based on an advert in a magazine or a poster in a gaming store. <p></p>If you love the game and want to see it grow. TALK about it. Run demos at gaming conventions and stores in your area. It's a grassroots kind of thing.</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
