<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#A0D5FF">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>Alex R</b>
<br>17 November 2003</font></td><td width="80%"><font><b>So what went wrong with the original Earthdawn? revisited!</b>
<br>
<p>So what actually went wrong with Earthdawn?<p></p>Well, I do have all the 1st ed Products and most of the 2nd ed stuff from LRG as well (I didn&Acirc;&acute;t get around to buy the rest yet), which means I really like the Game.<p></p>The only Problem that Earthdawn has in my opinion is this:<p></p>The Game is hell for Beginners, especially the meaning of steps and the corresponding Dice.<p></p>everyone I have ever played Earthdawn with has complained about only this one thing, The Game has a wonderful Background, some of the Best sourcebooks ever made, and a Game system that really works, provided you know it really well, if you don&Acirc;&acute;t then you spend most of your time wondering what dice to use on the next roll. <p></p>The only thing to get new Earthdawn Players from running after encountering the step system is a group of experienced players who keep them at it up to the point where they have understood the system and get comfortable with it, and that takes anywhere from 3 to 10 sessions in my experience.<p></p>So what does that tell us for the new ED line?<p></p>More or less nothing as the Game system should not and will not be changed.<p></p>Otherwise it tells us that the best RedBrick can do is keep up the Quality of the Game, and we the fans can try to get new players to play the game long enough to realice that the system, as complicated as it seems at first is really good and works just perfectly.<p></p>For me, I just restarted my old ED Campaign (with two new Players), and can&Acirc;&acute;t wait to get my hands on the first new stuff.<p></p>So, Keep on RedBrick and don&Acirc;&acute;t let us wait to long for your first book.</p>
</font></td>
</tr>
</table>
<table cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" border="0" width="100%">
<tr bgcolor="#7EB4FA">
<td valign="top" width="20%"><font face="verdana,trebuchet,sans-serif" color="black" style="font-size: 11px"><b>Vaughn</b>
